Ghana, officially the Republic of Ghana, is a country in [West Africa](/West_Africa). It sits by the [Gulf of Guinea](/Gulf_of_Guinea) and the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) to its south, a boundary that has shaped its history and its destiny. To its west lies [Côte d'Ivoire](/C%C3%B4te_d%27Ivoire), to the north, [Burkina Faso](/Burkina_Faso), and to the east, [Togo](/Togo). These borders, like most, are arbitrary lines on a map, but they define the space, the people, the narrative. Ghana stretches across 239,567 km² (92,497 sq mi), a landscape that shifts from the dry savannas of the coast to the dense, humid embrace of [tropical rainforests](/Tropical_rainforest). It’s a land of contrasts, a microcosm of the continent’s diverse ecologies. With a population of 35 million, it’s a significant presence, the thirteenth-most populous nation in Africa, and the second in West Africa. The capital, [Accra](/Accra), is the heart, a chaotic, vibrant entity. But other cities – [Tema](/Tema), [Kumasi](/Kumasi), [Sunyani](/Sunyani), [Ho](/Ho,_Ghana), [Cape Coast](/Cape_Coast), [Techiman](/Techiman), [Tamale](/Tamale,_Ghana), [Bolga](/Bolga), [Wa](/Wa,_Ghana), and [Sekondi-Takoradi](/Sekondi-Takoradi) – each hold their own stories, their own pulse.

The earliest whispers of civilization here speak of the [Bonoman](/Bono_state) kingdom in the south, and the [Kingdom of Dagbon](/Kingdom_of_Dagbon) in the north, with Bonoman already established by the 11th century. Then came the [Asante Empire](/Asante_Empire) and other Akan kingdoms, building their power, their legacy. From the 15th century, the Portuguese, and later other European powers, descended, drawn by the lure of trade, the glint of gold. It was a contest, a struggle for dominance, until the British finally asserted their control over the coast in the 19th century. Over a hundred years of resistance, of negotiation, of conflict, shaped the borders we see today. Four distinct British colonial territories – [Gold Coast](/Gold_Coast_(British_colony)), [Ashanti](/Ashanti_(Crown_Colony)), the [Northern Territories](/Northern_Territories_of_the_Gold_Coast), and [British Togoland](/British_Togoland) – were unified. In 1957, Ghana emerged, the first colony in Sub-Saharan Africa to gain sovereignty, a dominion within the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations). Under the iron will of President [Kwame Nkrumah](/Kwame_Nkrumah), it became a beacon, a voice in the global chorus of [decolonisation efforts](/Decolonisation_of_Africa) and the [Pan-African movement](/Pan-Africanism). A bold declaration, a new chapter etched in the annals of history.

Ghana is a tapestry of [ethnic](/Multi-ethnic) and linguistic threads, interwoven with a spectrum of religious beliefs. The [Akan](/Akan_people) are the largest group, but they form a plurality, not an absolute majority. [Christians](/Christianity_in_Ghana) are the dominant force (71.3%), with a significant [Muslim](/Islam_in_Ghana) minority (nearly a fifth), and a persistent adherence to [traditional faiths](/African_traditional_religion) or a declaration of no faith. It’s a complex spiritual landscape. Politically, Ghana is a unitary [constitutional democracy](/Liberal_democracy), governed by a [president](/President_of_Ghana) who is both head of state and [head of government](/Head_of_government). It’s a system that strives for stability. And in Africa, stability is a rare and precious commodity. Ghana ranks high in the [Ibrahim Index of African Governance](/Ibrahim_Index_of_African_Governance) and the [Fragile States Index](/Fragile_States_Index), a testament to its resilience. Since 1993, it has cultivated a reputation for freedom and stability, performing commendably in [healthcare](/Healthcare_in_Ghana), [economic](/Economy_of_Ghana) growth, and human development. Its influence resonates across West Africa and beyond. It’s a founding member of the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Ghana_and_the_Non-Aligned_Movement) and the [African Union](/African_Union), a participant in the [Economic Community of West African States](/Economic_Community_of_West_African_States), the [Group of 24](/Group_of_24), and the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations). A nation deeply enmeshed in the global web.

### Etymology

The name Ghana is borrowed from the [Wagadu](/Ghana_Empire) empire, a powerful entity that flourished in West Africa from the 3rd to the 12th centuries. Arab traders, engaged in the intricate dance of the [trans-Saharan trade](/Trans-Saharan_trade), knew this empire as Ghana. The name itself is believed to derive from *Kaya Maghan*, the title of Wagadu's rulers, meaning "ruler of gold." A fitting moniker for an empire built on such wealth. When the [Gold Coast colony](/Gold_Coast_(British_colony)) was on the cusp of independence, its future leader, [Kwame Nkrumah](/Kwame_Nkrumah) – a figure who, along with [The Big Six](/The_Big_Six_(Ghana)), steered the nation towards its destiny – chose Ghana. It was a deliberate act, an attempt to forge a unified identity, to evoke a shared past, a legacy of strength and liberation. The name resonated, a powerful symbol of aspiration, of self-determination, of a future built on dignity and resilience.

### History

#### Medieval kingdoms

The early chapters of Ghana's history are written in the rise and fall of kingdoms. [Bonoman](/Bono_state) in the south, and the [Kingdom of Dagbon](/Kingdom_of_Dagbon) in the north, laid the foundations. Bonoman existed as early as the 11th century. Later, from the 17th century, the Akan people began to coalesce into distinct states, their fortunes tied to the lucrative gold trade. These included Bonoman (in the Brong-Ahafo region), [Adansi](/Adansi), [Asante](/Asante_Empire) (in the Ashanti Region), [Denkyira](/Denkyira) (in the Western North region), the [Mankessim Kingdom](/Mankessim_Kingdom) (in the Central region), [Akyem](/Akyem), and [Akwamu](/Akwamu) (in the Eastern Region). By the 19th century, the [Asante Kingdom](/Ashanti_Empire) had become a dominant force in the southern territories. Its governance evolved from a loose confederation to a centralized kingdom, with its administrative heart in [Kumasi](/Kumasi). Before their extensive contact with Europeans, the Akan people had already established a robust economy, primarily based on gold and [gold bar](/Gold_bar) trading, a network that extended across various African states.

Meanwhile, the Ga-Dangme and Ewe peoples journeyed westward from what is now southwestern [Nigeria](/Nigeria). The Ewe, once known as Dogbo, migrated from the Oyo region, their path marked by settlements in Benin and Togo, eventually reaching Nortsie, a fortified town in present-day Togo, which served as their final dispersal point. Their departure from Nortsie was precipitated by the oppressive rule of King Agorkorli. The Ewe in Ghana speak three main dialects: Anlo along the coast, Tongu along the Volta River, and Ewedome in the hilly interior. The [Ga-Dangme](/Ga-Adangbe_people) settled in the Greater Accra Region and parts of the Eastern Region, while the Ewe are found in the [Volta Region](/Volta_Region) and neighboring Togo, Benin, and Nigeria.

#### European contact and colonialism

The Portuguese were the first Europeans to make their mark, establishing the [Portuguese Gold Coast](/Portuguese_Gold_Coast) with the construction of [Elmina Castle](/Elmina_Castle) (Castelo da Mina) in 1482. This imposing structure stands as the oldest European building in Sub-Saharan Africa, a silent witness to centuries of trade, exploitation, and the ebb and flow of power.

Trade between the Akan and European powers began in earnest in the 15th century. The Portuguese, captivated by the region's gold, established a trading post at a settlement they renamed [São Jorge da Mina](/Elmina). In 1481, King [John II of Portugal](/John_II_of_Portugal) dispatched [Diogo de Azambuja](/Diogo_de_Azambuja) to build what would become Elmina Castle, a formidable stronghold completed three years later. By 1598, the [Dutch](/Dutch_people) had joined the fray, carving out their own [Dutch Gold Coast](/Dutch_Gold_Coast) and constructing forts at [Fort Komenda](/Fort_Komenda) and Kormantsi. The Dutch eventually wrested control of Elmina Castle from the Portuguese in 1617 and captured Axim in 1642.

The 17th century saw other European traders, including the [Swedes](/Swedes) and [Denmark–Norway](/Denmark%E2%80%93Norway), establish their own coastal footholds – the [Swedish Gold Coast](/Swedish_Gold_Coast) and the [Danish Gold Coast](/Danish_Gold_Coast). This era was also deeply entangled with the brutal [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade), with over thirty forts and castles erected along the coast by European merchants. The Germans, too, made their bid with the [Brandenburger Gold Coast](/Brandenburger_Gold_Coast). By 1874, Great Britain had consolidated its influence, designating significant portions of the territory as the [British Gold Coast](/Gold_Coast_(British_colony)). The path to British dominance was not without its struggles. Fierce [military](/Military) clashes erupted between British colonial forces and the Akan nation-states. The [Ashanti Empire](/Ashanti_Empire), in particular, proved a formidable opponent, repelling the British in several [Anglo-Ashanti wars](/Anglo-Ashanti_wars) before ultimately succumbing in the [War of the Golden Stool](/War_of_the_Golden_Stool) in 1900. Amidst this colonial struggle, cocoa cultivation began to flourish in the tropical forests, supported by the British administration, laying the groundwork for a significant commercial industry.

#### Transition to independence

The seeds of independence were sown in the mid-20th century. In 1947, the [United Gold Coast Convention](/United_Gold_Coast_Convention), led by the influential ["The Big Six"](/The_Big_Six_(Ghana)), began advocating for "self-government within the shortest possible time," a sentiment fueled by the [1946 Gold Coast legislative election](/1946_Gold_Coast_general_election). [Kwame Nkrumah](/Kwame_Nkrumah), a charismatic nationalist and future first [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Ghana) and [president](/President_of_Ghana), broke away in 1949 to form the [Convention People's Party (CPP)](/Convention_People%27s_Party), with the rallying cry "self-government now." His strategy involved "positive action" – a campaign of non-violent protests, strikes, and civil disobedience. Nkrumah's activism led to his imprisonment, but even from behind bars, his influence grew. In the [1951 Gold Coast general election](/1951_Gold_Coast_general_election), he was elected to Parliament, and subsequently released. By 1952, he was prime minister, initiating a policy of Africanization to empower local leadership.

At the stroke of midnight on 6 March 1957, a new era dawned. The Gold Coast, Ashanti, the Northern Territories, and [British Togoland](/British_Togoland) were united as the independent dominion of Ghana, a member of the [British Commonwealth](/Commonwealth_of_Nations), under the [Ghana Independence Act 1957](/Ghana_Independence_Act_1957). The iconic [flag of Ghana](/Flag_of_Ghana) – red, gold, green, and a black star – was unfurled, symbolizing this newfound unity. On 1 July 1960, following a constitutional referendum and presidential election, Nkrumah declared Ghana a republic, becoming its first president. This date is now celebrated as [Republic Day](/Republic_Day), while 6 March remains the nation's [Independence Day](/Independence_Day_(Ghana)).

Nkrumah's leadership, however, was not without its autocratic tendencies. He presided over an [authoritarian](/Authoritarianism) regime, suppressing political dissent and conducting elections that lacked genuine fairness. In 1964, a constitutional amendment transformed Ghana into a [one-party state](/One-party_state), with Nkrumah declared [president for life](/President_for_life). Nkrumah was a fervent advocate of [Pan-Africanism](/Pan-Africanism), a vision ignited during his studies in the United States, drawing inspiration from figures like [Marcus Garvey](/Marcus_Garvey). He integrated the philosophies of Garvey, [Martin Luther King Jr.](/Martin_Luther_King_Jr.), and [W. E. B. Du Bois](/W._E._B._Du_Bois) into his vision for 1960s Ghana. Known as Osagyefo Dr. Kwame Nkrumah, he was a key architect of the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Non-Aligned_Movement) and established the [Kwame Nkrumah Ideological Institute](/Kwame_Nkrumah_Ideological_Institute) to propagate his ideologies of [communism](/Communism) and [socialism](/Socialism). His legacy was celebrated during his centenary, and his birthday was designated a [public holiday in Ghana](/Public_holidays_in_Ghana), [Founders' Day](/Founders%27_Day_(Ghana)).

#### Operation Cold Chop and aftermath

Nkrumah's reign was abruptly ended by a coup, codenamed "Operation Cold Chop," orchestrated by the [Ghana Armed Forces](/Ghana_Armed_Forces). This occurred while Nkrumah was abroad, on a diplomatic mission to end the [Vietnam War](/Vietnam_War). The coup, led by Colonel [Emmanuel Kwasi Kotoka](/Emmanuel_Kwasi_Kotoka) and Brigadier Akwasi Afrifa, brought the [National Liberation Council (NLC)](/National_Liberation_Council), chaired by Lieutenant General [Joseph A. Ankrah](/Joseph_Arthur_Ankrah), to power.

From 1966 onwards, Ghana experienced a turbulent period of alternating military and civilian governments, often plagued by economic instability. This cycle culminated in the ascent of [Flight Lieutenant](/Flight_lieutenant) [Jerry John Rawlings](/Jerry_Rawlings) and the [Provisional National Defence Council (PNDC)](/Provisional_National_Defence_Council) in 1981. The constitution was suspended, and [political parties](/List_of_political_parties_in_Ghana) were banned. The economy, predictably, suffered. Rawlings eventually navigated Ghana through a structural adjustment program, initiating reforms that stabilized the economy by the mid-1980s. A new constitution, reinstating [multi-party system](/Multi-party_system) politics, was promulgated for the [presidential election of 1992](/1992_Ghanaian_presidential_election), which Rawlings won. He was re-elected in the [general election of 1996](/1996_Ghanaian_general_election).

In 1994, a brutal [tribal war](/Konkomba%E2%80%93Nanumba_conflict) erupted in [Northern Ghana](/Northern_Region_(Ghana)), pitting the [Konkomba](/Konkomba_people) against other ethnic groups like the [Nanumba](/Nanumba_people), [Dagomba](/Dagomba_people), and [Gonja](/Gonja_people). The conflict resulted in the deaths of 1,000 to 2,000 people and displaced 150,000 more.

[Traditional chiefs](/Chieftaincy) in 2015 – a lingering influence.

The [2000 general election](/2000_Ghanaian_general_election) marked a significant transition. [John Kufuor](/John_Kufuor) of the [New Patriotic Party (NPP)](/New_Patriotic_Party) became president, a peaceful transfer of power from one elected leader to another, a landmark achievement for the Fourth Republic.

The [2008 general election](/2008_Ghanaian_general_election) saw a close contest, with [John Atta Mills](/John_Atta_Mills) of the [National Democratic Congress (NDC)](/National_Democratic_Congress_(Ghana)) narrowly defeating the NPP candidate. Mills's untimely death in 2012 led to Vice President [John Mahama](/John_Mahama) assuming the presidency. Mahama then secured his own mandate in the [2012 general election](/2012_Ghanaian_general_election), solidifying Ghana's reputation as a "stable democracy." However, the [2016 general election](/2016_Ghanaian_general_election) brought [Nana Akufo-Addo](/Nana_Akufo-Addo) to power. He was re-elected in a closely fought [election in 2020](/2020_Ghanaian_general_election). Akufo-Addo's tenure concluded in January 2025, with [John Mahama](/John_Mahama) succeeding him as president.

In an effort to combat deforestation, Ghana launched "Green Ghana Day" on 11 June 2021, with an ambitious goal of planting five million trees. A necessary gesture, perhaps, against the relentless march of environmental degradation.

### Geography

#### Overview

Ghana lies on the [Gulf of Guinea](/Gulf_of_Guinea) in [West Africa](/West_Africa), a mere few degrees north of the [Equator](/Equator). It covers 238,540 km² (92,101 sq mi) and boasts a coastline of approximately 560 kilometers (350 miles) along the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean). Geographically, it’s nestled between latitudes 4°45′N and 11°N, and longitudes 1°15′E and 3°15′W. An interesting quirk: the [Prime Meridian](/Prime_Meridian) slices through [Tema](/Tema), near Accra, making Ghana the country closest to the theoretical point of origin (0°, 0°) – a spot that lies offshore in the Atlantic.

The landscape is a mosaic of [grasslands](/Savanna), [coastal shrublands](/Biome), and [tropical rainforests](/Tropical_rainforest). Forests extend inland from the coast for about 320 kilometers (200 miles) and creep eastward for another 270 kilometers (170 miles), providing resources for mining and timber. Ghana is home to five distinct terrestrial ecoregions: [Eastern Guinean forests](/Eastern_Guinean_forests), [Guinean forest–savanna mosaic](/Guinean_forest%E2%80%93savanna_mosaic), [West Sudanian savanna](/West_Sudanian_savanna), [Central African mangroves](/Central_African_mangroves), and [Guinean mangroves](/Guinean_mangroves). A rich biodiversity, often overlooked.

The [White Volta](/White_Volta) and its tributary, the [Black Volta](/Black_Volta), carve their way south through Ghana, eventually feeding into [Lake Volta](/Lake_Volta). This vast reservoir, created by the hydroelectric [Akosombo Dam](/Akosombo_Dam) completed in 1965, is the world's third-largest by volume and largest by surface area. The Volta River then flows from the lake into the [Gulf of Guinea](/Gulf_of_Guinea). The northernmost point of Ghana is Pulmakong, near the Burkina Faso border, while the southernmost tip is [Cape Three Points](/Cape_Three_Points).

