#### Landmarks, borders and regions

*   **[Coastal Plain](/Geography_of_Ghana)**: Home to [Accra](/Accra), [Apam](/Apam), [Cape Coast](/Cape_Coast), [Elmina](/Elmina), [Kakum National Park](/Kakum_National_Park), [Kokrobite](/Kokrobite), [Nzulezo](/Nzulezo), [Sekondi-Takoradi](/Sekondi-Takoradi), and [Ada Foah](/Ada_Foah). This is where the [Gulf of Guinea](/Gulf_of_Guinea) meets the land, a region of [coastal plains](/Coastal_plain), the seat of government, historic castles and forts, and the remnants of [rainforest](/Rainforest).

*   **[Ashanti-Kwahu](/Geography_of_Ghana)**: Centered around [Koforidua](/Koforidua), [Kumasi](/Kumasi), [Obuasi](/Obuasi), and [Sunyani](/Sunyani). This is the heartland of forested hills and the historic [Kingdom of Ashanti](/Kingdom_of_Ashanti).

*   **[Volta Basin](/Volta_Basin)**: Dominated by [Lake Volta](/Lake_Volta), this region includes [Tamale](/Tamale,_Ghana). It’s defined by the vast river system feeding the lake and Ghana's eastern [border crossing](/Border_crossing) points.

*   **[Northern Plains](/Geography_of_Ghana)**: Encompassing [Wa](/Wa,_Ghana), [Bolgatanga](/Bolgatanga), and [Mole National Park](/Mole_National_Park). This is the realm of [savanna](/Savanna) plains, historic [trade routes](/Trade_route), and northern [border crossing](/Border_crossing) points.

### Climate

#### Overview

Ghana experiences a [tropical climate](/Tropical_climate), marked by distinct [wet season](/Wet_season) and [dry season](/Dry_season). Its location places it at the convergence of three major hydro-climatic zones. The [eastern coastal belt](/Dahomey_Gap) is warm and relatively dry, the [south-west corner](/Biome) is hot and [humid](/Humidity), and the northern regions are characterized by heat and dryness.

The specter of [climate change in Ghana](/Climate_change_in_Ghana) looms large, impacting everything from infrastructure and hydropower to [food security](/Food_security) and [water supply](/Water_supply). Rising temperatures, unpredictable [rainfall](/Rainfall), and more frequent [extreme weather](/Extreme_weather) events like [droughts](/Drought), [wild fires](/Wildfire), and [floods](/Flood) threaten [livelihoods](/Livelihood) in [agriculture](/Agriculture) and fisheries. Coastal erosion due to [sea-level rise](/Sea_level_rise) is another pressing concern. Ghana's economy, heavily reliant on [climate-sensitive](/Climate_sensitivity) sectors, is particularly vulnerable. Diseases like [malaria](/Malaria), [dengue fever](/Dengue_fever), and [cholera](/Cholera) are predicted to increase as water conditions change. Despite these challenges, Ghana has committed to action, signing the [Paris Agreement](/Paris_Agreement) in 2016 and setting a target to reduce [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions) by 64 million metric tons by 2030, with a long-term goal of [net zero](/Net-zero_emissions) by 2060.

#### Relief and regions

The terrain of Ghana is varied: low [coastal plains](/Coastal_Plain) give way to forested hills in the center, and then to the expansive [savanna](/Savanna) of the north. Geographically, it can be divided into four main areas:
*   The [Coastal Plain](/Geography_of_Ghana) along the Gulf of Guinea.
*   The Ashanti uplands in the central part of the country.
*   The [Volta Basin](/Volta_Basin) in the east, dominated by the immense [Lake Volta](/Lake_Volta).
*   The [Northern Plains](/Geography_of_Ghana) stretching towards Burkina Faso.

The highest point in Ghana is [Mount Afadja](/Mount_Afadja) (885 m), located in the Akwapim-Togo Range.

#### Hydrology

The [Volta River](/Volta_River) system is the lifeblood of Ghana's water resources. Its principal tributaries, the [White Volta](/White_Volta) and [Black Volta](/Black_Volta), converge in the north before flowing into [Lake Volta](/Lake_Volta), one of the world's largest artificial reservoirs. Created by the [Akosombo Dam](/Akosombo_Dam) in 1965, the lake is a critical source of [hydropower](/Hydropower). The Volta River eventually empties into the Gulf of Guinea, east of Accra. Other significant rivers include the [Pra River](/Pra_River_(Ghana)), [Ankobra River](/Ankobra_River), and [Tano River](/Tano_River).

#### Extremities

Ghana's geographic boundaries are marked by Pulmakong, the northernmost settlement near the Burkina Faso border, and [Cape Three Points](/Cape_Three_Points), its southernmost point.

### Politics

#### Overview

Ghana is a [unitary](/Unitary_executive_theory) [presidential](/Presidential_system) [constitutional democracy](/Liberal_democracy). Its political landscape is characterized by a parliamentary [multi-party system](/Multi-party_system), largely dominated by two major parties: the [National Democratic Congress (NDC)](/National_Democratic_Congress_(Ghana)) and the [New Patriotic Party (NPP)](/New_Patriotic_Party). The nation transitioned from a history of civilian and military rule to the Fourth Republic in January 1993, following the presidential and parliamentary elections of late 1992. The current [constitution of Ghana](/Constitution_of_Ghana), enacted in 1992, delineates powers among the [President of Ghana](/President_of_Ghana) (also [commander-in-chief](/Commander-in-chief) of the [Ghana Armed Forces](/Ghana_Armed_Forces)), the [Parliament of Ghana](/Parliament_of_Ghana), the [Cabinet of Ghana](/Cabinet_of_Ghana), the [Ghanaian Council of State](/Council_of_State_(Ghana)), and an independent [Judiciary of Ghana](/Judiciary_of_Ghana). Elections are held every four years under [universal suffrage](/Universal_suffrage).

Presidential terms are limited to two four-year mandates. [Nana Akufo-Addo](/Nana_Akufo-Addo) secured the presidency in the [general election in 2016](/2016_Ghanaian_general_election), defeating the incumbent [John Mahama](/John_Mahama). He was subsequently re-elected in the [2020 election](/2020_Ghanaian_general_election), a result that was contested in the Supreme Court. Akufo-Addo's presidency concluded in January 2025, with [John Mahama](/John_Mahama) assuming the role of president.

Ghana has consistently demonstrated political stability. The [Fragile States Index](/Fragile_States_Index) of 2012 ranked it as the 67th least fragile state globally and fifth in Africa. Furthermore, the 2012 [Transparency International Corruption Perception Index](/Corruption_Perceptions_Index) placed Ghana at 64th out of 174 countries for low corruption, and fifth in Africa. The [Ibrahim Index of African Governance](/Ibrahim_Index_of_African_Governance) (2012) ranked it seventh on the continent, highlighting its success in delivering essential political goods to its citizens. According to the 2023 [V-Dem Democracy indices](/V-Dem_Democracy_indices), Ghana stands as the 67th electoral democracy worldwide and the 10th in Africa, indicating a robust democratic framework.

#### Foreign relations

Since gaining independence, Ghana has been a staunch advocate for nonalignment, playing a pivotal role in the founding of the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Non-Aligned_Movement). It champions international and regional cooperation, actively participating in the [United Nations](/United_Nations) and the [African Union](/African_Union).

Ghana maintains a strong diplomatic relationship with the United States. The country has hosted multiple U.S. presidents – [Bill Clinton](/Bill_Clinton), [George W. Bush](/George_W._Bush), and [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) – as well as Vice President [Kamala Harris](/Kamala_Harris). Ghanaian diplomats and public figures have held significant positions in international organizations, including former UN Secretary-General [Kofi Annan](/Kofi_Annan), [International Criminal Court](/International_Criminal_Court) Judge [Akua Kuenyehia](/Akua_Kuenyehia), and former Presidents [Jerry John Rawlings](/Jerry_Rawlings) and [John Agyekum Kufuor](/John_Kufuor), who served as UN diplomats.

In September 2010, President [John Atta Mills](/John_Atta_Mills) visited China, where he and then-[General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party](/General_secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party) [Hu Jintao](/Hu_Jintao) commemorated 50 years of [diplomatic ties](/China%E2%80%93Ghana_relations). China reciprocated this engagement, with a visit from Zhou Tienong, vice-chairman of the [Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China](/Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People%27s_Congress), in November 2011, meeting with President [John Mahama](/John_Mahama). Chinese investment has become a significant factor in Ghana's economy, focusing on infrastructure, natural resources, and manufacturing. While these investments have spurred growth and job creation, concerns about project sustainability, environmental impact, and transparency persist.

In 2013, Iranian President [Mahmoud Ahmadinejad](/Mahmoud_Ahmadinejad) met with Mahama to discuss strengthening the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Non-Aligned_Movement) and fostering bilateral relations.

Ghana has integrated the [Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)](/Sustainable_Development_Goals_and_Ghana) into its national agenda, employing a decentralized planning approach that encourages stakeholder participation. The country was recognized for being the first Sub-Saharan African nation to achieve the goal of halving poverty, as outlined in Goal 1 of the [Millennium Development Goals](/Millennium_Development_Goals).

#### Military

The [Ghana Armed Forces (GAF)](/Ghana_Armed_Forces) began with a modest structure in 1957, comprising headquarters, support services, infantry battalions, and an armored reconnaissance squadron. President Nkrumah harbored ambitions of rapidly expanding the GAF to support his vision of a [United States of Africa](/United_States_of_Africa). This led to the establishment of additional battalions and a parachute airborne unit in the early 1960s. Today, Ghana is recognized as a [regional power](/Regional_power) and [regional hegemon](/Regional_hegemony). The GAF has earned high praise for its professionalism and effectiveness, as noted by [Canadian Forces](/Canadian_Armed_Forces) commander [Roméo Dallaire](/Rom%C3%A9o_Dallaire) in his book [Shake Hands with the Devil](/Shake_Hands_with_the_Devil_(book)). The military's operations and doctrine are guided by the constitution, military strategy documents, and agreements such as those from the [Kofi Annan International Peacekeeping Training Centre](/Kofi_Annan_International_Peacekeeping_Training_Centre). Though Ghana is generally peaceful, political grievances have, at times, sparked localized violence.

#### Law enforcement

The primary law enforcement agencies are the [Ghana Police Service](/Ghana_Police_Service) and its [Criminal Investigation Department](/Criminal_Investigation_Department), responsible for crime detection, maintaining order, and ensuring internal security. The Ghana Police Service operates through eleven specialized units, including a [Militarized police](/Militarized_police) [Rapid Deployment Force](/Rapid_deployment_force) and a [Marine Police Unit](/Ghana_Police_Service). These forces are organized into ten regional divisions, with additional units dedicated to the port city of [Tema](/Tema) and maritime security. The Marine Police Unit specifically addresses issues related to the country's offshore [oil and gas industry](/Oil_and_gas_industry). Incarceration is managed by the [Ghana Prisons Service](/Ghana_Prisons_Service), which includes the [Borstal Institute for Juveniles](/Borstal_Institute_for_Juveniles). Ghana retains the death penalty for severe offenses. The pursuit of justice and effective, accountable institutions is an ongoing endeavor, aligned with global [Sustainable Development Goals](/Sustainable_Development_Goals).

Ghana serves as a critical transit point for international drug trafficking, particularly for narcotics originating from South America destined for Europe. The country's porous borders and underdeveloped border control infrastructure make it vulnerable. The narcotics trade operates largely as an [underground economy](/Black_market), often operating beyond public awareness. The geographical location along the Gulf of Guinea further enhances its appeal to drug cartels. Despite efforts by the [Narcotics Control Board](/Narcotics_Control_Board_(Ghana)), which has seized significant quantities of cocaine, drug seizures have seen a decline in recent years, suggesting evolving tactics by traffickers. The presence of established smuggling organizations contributes to Ghana's role in this illicit trade.

#### Human rights

[Homosexual acts](/Homosexuality) are legally prohibited in Ghana, and societal acceptance remains extremely low, with a 2013 [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) survey indicating 96% of Ghanaians believe homosexuality should not be accepted. In some rural areas, elderly [women in Ghana](/Women_in_Ghana) are sometimes accused of [witchcraft](/Witchcraft), leading to the existence of so-called [witch camps](/Witch_camp) housing around 1,000 individuals. The government has expressed an intention to close these camps.

### Economy

#### Overview

Ghana possesses a rich array of [industrial minerals](/Industrial_mineral), [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon), and [precious metals](/Precious_metal). It is recognized as an emerging [digital economy](/Digital_economy) with a [mixed economy](/Mixed_economy) structure and is classified as an [emerging market](/Emerging_market). The nation has set forth an ambitious economic blueprint, "Ghana Vision 2020," aiming to become a [developed country](/Developed_country) by 2029 and a [newly industrialized country](/Newly_industrialized_country) by 2039. This vision places Ghana among the vanguard of African economic development.

Ghana's economic ties extend to the [Chinese yuan renminbi](/Renminbi), bolstered by its substantial gold reserves. In 2013, the [Bank of Ghana](/Bank_of_Ghana) began circulating the renminbi as a secondary national trade currency, alongside the national [Ghanaian cedi](/Ghanaian_cedi).

Poverty remains a significant concern, with a stark contrast between urban and rural areas. In 2012-2013, 38% of rural dwellers faced poverty, compared to just 11% in urban areas. Urban centers offer greater employment opportunities, particularly in informal trade, while rural poverty is largely concentrated within the agricultural sector.

#### Energy

The [Volta River Authority](/Volta_River_Authority) and the [Ghana National Petroleum Corporation](/Ghana_National_Petroleum_Corporation), both state-owned entities, are the primary electricity producers. The [Akosombo Dam](/Akosombo_Dam), constructed on the Volta River in 1965, along with the [Bui Dam](/Bui_Dam), the [Kpong Dam](/Kpong_Dam), and other hydroelectric facilities, form the backbone of the nation's [hydropower](/Hydropower) generation. The government has also explored the development of a second nuclear power plant in Africa.

#### Finance

The [Ghana Stock Exchange](/Ghana_Stock_Exchange) ranks as the fifth largest in Africa and third in Sub-Saharan Africa, with a market capitalization of GH¢57.2 billion (CN¥180.4 billion) in 2012. It was the second best-performing stock exchange in Sub-Saharan Africa in 2013.

#### Agriculture and exports

Ghana is a major producer of high-quality [cocoa](/Cocoa_bean), ranking as the second-largest global producer. Its membership in the [ICCO](/International_Cocoa_Organization) facilitates international cocoa trade. Ghana is classified as a middle-income country. The [services sector](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy) contributes the largest share to GDP (50%), followed by manufacturing (24.1%), [extractive industries](/Primary_sector_of_the_economy) (5%), and taxes (20.9%).

#### Industry and technology

Ghana's economy is characterized by a growing manufacturing sector and the export of digital technology products. The country is also involved in the assembly and export of automobiles and ships. Its diverse export base includes industrial minerals and agricultural products, with cocoa being a primary commodity. Ghana is also a significant producer and exporter of [petroleum](/Petroleum) and [natural gas](/Natural_gas).

The [information and communications technology](/Information_and_communications_technology) (ICT) sector is a vital part of Ghana's industrial landscape, with companies like [Rlg Communications](/Rlg_Communications) spearheading the production of mobile devices and consumer electronics.

[Electric cars](/Electric_car) have been manufactured in Ghana since 2014, signaling a move towards greener transportation.

In a notable financial move, Ghana announced plans to issue government debt through social and green bonds in late 2021, becoming the first African country to do so. These bonds aim to refinance debt and fund social and environmental projects, including educational and health initiatives.

#### Natural resources

Ghana produces and exports [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon) such as [sweet crude oil](/Sweet_crude_oil) and natural gas. The state-owned [Ghana Oil Company](/Ghana_Oil_Company) is a leading player in the petroleum and gas sector, while the [Ghana National Petroleum Corporation](/Ghana_National_Petroleum_Corporation) oversees exploration and production. Ghana aims to significantly increase its oil and gas output. The discovery of the [Jubilee Oil Field](/Jubilee_Oil_Field) in 2007, containing substantial crude oil reserves, marked a turning point. Ghana is estimated to hold significant petroleum reserves, ranking among the largest in Africa and the world. The government has also explored nationalizing petroleum and natural gas reserves to enhance revenue.

In 2015, Ghana produced 88 metric tonnes of gold. By 2019, it had surpassed South Africa to become Africa's largest gold producer. Beyond gold, Ghana exports [silver](/Silver), timber, [diamonds](/Diamond), [bauxite](/Bauxite), and [manganese](/Manganese), with further mineral deposits awaiting exploitation. The government has considered nationalizing the mining industry to increase state revenue.

The electricity shortages of 2015 and 2016, known as [dumsor](/Dumsor), spurred increased interest in renewable energy sources. As of 2019, there is a surplus of electricity.

The [judicial system of Ghana](/Judiciary_of_Ghana) grapples with issues of corruption and economic malpractice. Transparency International's 2018 [Corruption Perceptions Index](/Corruption_Perceptions_Index) ranked Ghana 78th out of 180 countries, indicating perceived levels of public sector corruption.

### Science and technology

Ghana launched its cellular mobile network in 1992, followed by internet connectivity and [ADSL](/ADSL) broadband services. The country ranks 101st in the [Global Innovation Index](/Global_Innovation_Index) (2025).

The [Ghana Space Science and Technology Centre (GSSTC)](/Ghana_Space_Science_and_Technology_Centre) and the Ghana Space Agency (GhsA) are spearheading the nation's [space exploration](/Space_exploration) initiatives. Efforts are underway to launch a national security [observational satellite](/Earth_observation_satellite). Ghana allocates 1% of its GDP to space exploration and scientific research, and collaborates with the [South African National Space Agency](/South_African_National_Space_Agency).

### Tourism

In 2011, Ghana welcomed 1,087,000 tourists from various continents. The country offers a diverse range of attractions, including waterfalls like [Kintampo waterfalls](/Kintampo_waterfalls) and [Wli waterfalls](/Wli_waterfalls), palm-lined beaches, caves, mountains, and vast lakes such as [Lake Bosumtwi](/Lake_Bosumtwi) and the expansive [Lake Volta](/Lake_Volta). Historical sites include dozens of [forts and castles](/List_of_castles_in_Ghana), many designated [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Site). Notable among these are [Cape Coast Castle](/Cape_Coast_Castle_Museum) and [Elmina Castle](/Elmina_Castle), poignant reminders of the transatlantic slave trade and crucial repositories of African heritage. UNESCO has recognized these sites as significant monuments, shaping not only Ghana's history but the history of the world.

In 2010, the [World Economic Forum](/World_Economic_Forum) ranked Ghana 108th out of 139 countries in terms of tourist appeal. However, [Forbes](/Forbes) magazine in 2011 recognized Ghana as the 11th most friendly country globally, the highest ranking for an African nation. Tourism remains a significant earner of foreign exchange for Ghana. In 2024, Ghana was ranked the 55th most peaceful country in the world according to the [Global Peace Index](/Global_Peace_Index).

The coastline offers numerous surfing spots, attracting enthusiasts from around the globe.

According to Destination Pride, Ghana scores 22 out of 100 on its "Pride" index.

### Demographics

As of 2024, the United Nations estimates Ghana's population at 34,581,288. Approximately 29% of the population is under 15 years old, with the majority (57.8%) falling within the 15-64 age bracket. The 2010 census identified the largest ethnic groups as the [Akan](/Akan_people) (47.3%), [Mole-Dagbani](/Mole-Dagbon_people) (18.5%), [Ewe](/Ewe_people) (13.9%), [Ga-Dangme](/Ga-Dangme_people) (7.4%), [Gurma](/Gurma_people) (5.7%), and [Guan](/Guang_people) (3.7%). The median age of Ghanaian citizens is 21 years, reflecting a youthful population. Ghana accounts for 0.42% of the global population.

Ghana has seen an influx of [skilled workers](/Skilled_worker) holding [Ghana Cards](/Ghana_Card), contributing to small communities of Chinese, Malaysian, Indian, Middle Eastern, and European nationals. However, the [Ghana Immigration Service](/Ghana_Immigration_Service) has also reported significant numbers of [economic migrants](/Economic_migrant) and [undocumented immigrants](/Illegal_immigration_to_Ghana), predominantly from Nigeria, Burkina Faso, Togo, and Mali. Historically, Ghana has implemented measures to manage its foreign population; in 1969, the "Ghana Aliens Compliance Order" led to the deportation of over 3 million aliens. More recently, in 2013, thousands of undocumented miners, including Chinese nationals, were deported.

